    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-10-18T18:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-10-18T18:10:00-05:00" n="139"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d139">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.30/89: Airgram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Braden</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-10-18T19:10:00-04:00"
                            >October 18, 1943—7:10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>A–2382. Your A–2051, October 4.</p>
                <p>Department is aware that claims arising out of explosion of Army barge in harbor
                    of Habana can be considered under the Act of January 2, 1942, as amended, and
                    that they do not fall within jurisdiction of the Claims Commission provided for
                    in Article XII of Agreement for Military Cooperation of June 19, 1942. However,
                    this Government desired to obtain agreement of Cuban Government to submission of
                    all claims for damages arising from acts of members of the armed forces of the
                    United States in Cuba to Commissions provided for in the Act of January 2, 1942,
                    If Cuban Government is not agreeable to such an arrangement, this Government
                    does not desire to press the matter, and the War Department advises that it will
                    proceed to set up a Commission under the Act of January 2, 1942 to consider
                    Cuban claims. However, the existence of Article XII of the Agreement of June 19,
                    1942 is an impediment to the exercise by such a Commission of jurisdiction over
                    claims within the purview of Article XII. For this reason and, since the
                    obligations undertaken in Article XII cannot be carried out, this Government
                    considers its abrogation imperative. You will, therefore, please endeavor to
                    obtain the consent of the Cuban Government to such abrogation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
